reviews.text: Incredible. Have been three times and would go again and again. Don't have to be a war history buff to appreciate it. It is a true testament to this country's heroes that every Aussie needs to see, appreciate, understand and shed a tear over. It is a monument of pride and love. The best thing to see in Canberra! Was very moved. Warning: plan ahead for a DAY outing as there is so much to see! Wonderful memory!

More than a memorial or a view. The museum is fantastic, thoroughly informative, full of everything you would ever want.

Absolutely massive, put aside a few hours to explore at a steady pace. It's worth every minute and equally pass on appreciation to all who have given their lives or continue to do so within the forces. Highly recommended, amazing artifacts, vehicles, planes, soap etc everything! Perfectly done time capsule, just try not to miss a room. 

Definitely recommend and it's FREE!

I've never visited a place like this before! I was totally moved by the details presented at the memorial. 

It takes on an average a whole day to go through each section. Please keep more than a day for the visit. 

Please bring kids, if you have any! 

Loved it and will visit again for sure 🙂

Absolutely amazing experience. It is definitely a must see and do if you’re in Canberra or nearby. The travel into the city is so easy and it’s such a worth it attraction. You could spend so long in there, so make sure you leave yourself an hour at the absolute minimum. Such a great place.

A must visit for all tourists, schools and families. I had the privilege of visiting here as part of a visiting school group and was astounded as to the level of detail portrayed through their exhibitions. This place is a national treasure. The feeling you get while inside has to be experienced. Plenty of parking nearly. It's a definite destination for anyone planning a visit to the ACT.
A hidden gem inside the ANU - a small but recently renovated museum. Worth it just for the scale model of ancient Rome.

I was really excited to travel all the way from interstate to visit this "museum".
Honestly, I expected much more since I had read that it was being utilised as a teaching myseum for its tertiary  students.
I think the word 'museum' is very loosely used. It should be called a 'collection' of artifacts as the space is very small and to be honest,  there are not many artifacts to look at...
Unfortunately it does not compare to either the Classics Museum at Macquarie University or the Nicholson Museum at Sydney University...
Central desert exhibition is mind blowing and breathtaking. The river room is well worth spending some time in

The Drill Hall was built in 1940 to train soldiers for the Second World War. The 3rd Battalion, Werriwa Regiment was based in this building in 1941-2.

In 1984 the interior was superbly remodelled to create an art gallery which is considered one of the most beautiful of its kind. In 2004 a Heritage order was placed on the building.

While the National Gallery of Australia waited for the completion of its building, temporary exhibitions of the national collection were held here. In 1992 the Australian National University took over the Drill Hall Gallery as a showcase for its own art collection and as a venue for temporary exhibitions.There are 4 discrete exhibition spaces.

The Gallery is a venue of choice for many of Australia’s leading contemporary artists, curators and collectors. We have developed a proud tradition of impeccably presented landmark exhibitions accompanied by scholarly publications.

Sidney Nolan’s 9-panel panorama, Riverbend (recently nominated among the ten must-see art treasures of Canberra) is on permanent display in the RIVERBEND ROOM.

The Drill Hall Gallery provides the Canberra community and ANU with a selective program of high quality exhibitions of Australian and international art.

The Gallery supports the arts in the Canberra region by presenting exhibitions developed in conjunction with the University’s wide-ranging academic interests and or to coincide with major conferences and public events. National and international exhibitions – and works from the University’s own extensive collection – are features of the Gallery’s program.
Awesome gallery to escape the busyness of campus, great stuff and some interesting works shown.
If for no other reason, do me here to see the permanent exhibition of Sidney Nolan's Riverbend
Some interesting works in a an uncluttered, open space.

Went here when I first opened and had a great time.
As a young country many of the things it holds are remembered by many so it's always nice to see relics of the 50s.
Doesn't stand still either, which is nice.
Well worth a visit
Good exhibition on Chinese calligraphy & related. Excellent Friends room with good outlook but indifferent coffee. Entrance foyer has new ceiling art as well as my favourite caravan.

Love the exhibitions here and today went to experience the VR Antarctica Exhibition. Fantastic experience 'flying' over Antarctica and being able to turn 360 degrees in your chair and see what is in front, and behind.  Amazing scenery, and you could see all the detail in the landscape under your feet.
Really interesting visit. Lots to see for free. Spacious museum, lots of parking. Well worth a visit. Cafe, outdoor learning/play area.

I suggest visitors take a torch as some exhibits are poorly lit. Many of the information boards are way too low to read, requiring the visitor to bow or kneel so as the information is anything close to eye level. Too many exhibits belong in an art gallery and not a museum. More emphasis needs to place on the financial benefits many of the exhibits made and continue to make for Australia. Overall a pleasing visit.

The National Archives of Australia can best be described as the memory of our nation – collecting and preserving Australian Government records that reflect our history and identity.

The  collection traces events and decisions that have shaped the nation and the lives of Australians. Visitors are welcome to explore our collection, online or in person, to learn more.

As well as preserving  history, the National Archives plays a key role in helping to ensure the Australian Government and its departments are effective and accountable to the people.

Under the Archives Act 1983, the National Archives has two main roles:

To preserve Australia’s most valuable government records and encourage their use by the public; and to promote good records management by Australian Government agencies.
In fulfilling these responsibilities, it ensures that Australians have access to a national archival collection so they may better understand their heritage and democracy.

Through individuals’ interaction with various government departments, aspects of their lives are preserved for future generations. Family historians find a wealth of information in our records, as do academics and other researchers.

Caught the Walter Burley Griffin exhibition which was really interesting both architecturally, artistically and from a town planning point of view. There are some interesting things to see, but it's probably not for everyone. I enjoyed looking through some of the historical photos being displayed.
Awesome visit. Really friendly staff.
It's interesting to be able to find odd news articles about Australia's past. It is also a good starting point to research Canberra's history, or your own.
Good galleries though not many. Great service.

Went to see free exhibition (Cook and the Pacific) with the kids, one in a pram. Staff were great, no issues. Will need to go back sans children, so I can have a proper look.

Not the first exhibition I have seen there, always well curated and full of interesting items.

Great location overlooking the lake, surrounded by public art and part of the parliamentary triangle. Has a cafe, bookshop, paid parking. 

They have a reading room too.
A good place for kids, safe and continent facilities for them.

Wonderful place to do some studying or research.
Chair looks comfy and the view from the windows is just relaxing.
River side walking trail let you relax your brain if you study in the library for extended hours.

Fantastic resource for all, not just those who live in Canberra. Special mention to Sonja who was incredibly helpful when my friend and I visited. Good to know that the hold every book published in Australia!

A national treasure with a collection rivaling the great libraries of the world. Calm environment for research and study; excellent amenities (clean toilets,  free lockers, water fountains). There is also a bit for the visitor too with exhibits and galleries on rotation.  Bookplate is a very popular restaurant with spectacular views across the lake,  and they cater for vegans. Free wifi and ample parking.

This is a very well laid out gallery. There are many early works, including many of prominent Aboriginal people and early pioneers. There are sculptures as well as paintings and sketches. Although I found much of it interesting, there are probably too many displays to make seeing the whole gallery a totally enjoyable experience. On the other hand, there is so much information about each of the items that it would be difficult to rush through too quickly.  It's great that our explorers, Australia's original people and business, sport and political figures are acknowledged with a portrait in the gallery. There is paid car parking below and a cafe.

Amazing! Spent hours here. So interesting and so much to see. We didn’t want to leave. On the day we visited it was quiet and relaxed and the perfect activity for a cold rainy day in Canberra. Will be back here again for sure.
A beautiful space. The collection is very diverse and incredibly high quality. The staff are friendly and helpful.

Mostly really good. 
Did have issues getting around with the pram and nappy bag as security was pretty tough. Recommend you take minimal on the day. Very basic parent room but it does the job. 
Echoed a bit (noticed when my newborn wouldn't stop farting lol). 
Well displayed artwork and pretty easy parking. Cafe was pretty good too.

NGA is a world class gallery, a large gallery comparable to those interstate and overseas. There are permanent and touring exhibitions, featuring a mix of contemporary and traditional art from Western and global artists. Something for everyone, suited to all ages and physical abilities. Good selection of indigenous art, and well curated selection of Australian art generally.

Great mix of history and Australian culture in an inviting format which does not feel dry. Lots of knowledgeable volunteers and staff floating around. Loved walking into the many different rooms and the cartoon exhibition is fantastic. Will definitely be back!

Went to old Parliament House for enlighten and they had all of these records on display. It was a part of an art display that allowed us the audience to write down a song/s that defined us and why. Super cool intuitive and super cool building. Would go to visit again.

Otherwise known as the MOAD (Ministry Of Australian Democracy) this is a preserved piece of Australian history from the mid 1980's. Lots to see and many rooms to explore, it provides an insight into political life from the last century. The retro decorations are funny today, but were quite modern 40 years ago. I didn't have time to see everything so I will be going back, worth including on your list of places to visit in Canberra.

Love this place. A great musuem for all ages. A good place to learn a bit about our democracy, past and present. Plenty of exhibitions and events happen around here too. I recommend to anyone who is interested in recent history of Australia.

Visited during the enlightenment festival for the first time.  Awesome access, not your typical museum experience.   If you are interested in Australian history or just a retro look at at 70's or 80's style work place check this place out.

Simply wow !
What an informative place to visit and learn so much about Australia 🇦🇺 and Australian politics. 
Anyone including tourists and non-Australians are welcomed. 
Appointments are not needed simply head up and get entry after security check up. No separate entrance for tourists and politicians. 
One can go to both Parliament and Senate and listen the speeches from Senators, MP, Prime Ministers etc live. 
When Parliament is not in session public are allowed to inside Chambers otherwise public is allowed in the viewing decks. 
Free tours are also offered but one has to sign up for the tours at reception. 
There is a shop and a cafe aswell. 
Parking is paid. 
You can easily head up to rooftop via lifts. 
Fun fact: The whole map of Australian Parliament is printed on 5$ note.

It's a shame Canberra gets its reputation from the politics that goes on in the building. Everything about this place is amazing, and should always be one of the places people visit when in the city. The staff of all levels are fantastic and should be commended on their professionalism.

Nice modern building to showcase Australian democracy. They have showcased nice portraits big former prime minister's but it's ironic to see that most of the prime minister's didn't completer the term(many of them were prime minister for about an year and there was one just for a week).
Went on the weekend. Free parking. Was not that busy. Easy to move around. To learn more about the place - go on a tour.

Highly recommend the free guided tours, which were very informative. Learn about the architecture and symbolism of the building, how bills are passed and more. Take the lift near the House of Representatives chamber to the roof.

The cafe makes amazing pizza. We even saw a family have high tea.

My school does their swimming carnivals here every year for as long as I can remember. The facilities in the aquatic centre are very good but sometimes results weren't counted because some kids didn't push the timing board had enough, and there was spiders in the bathrooms one year. I think that they could have more sensitive timing boards and work on their bathroom cleanliness a bit. other than that it was great!

Took a tour with my kids and they loved it! The interactive sports center was their highlight! Being the middle of summer holidays there were no athletes training and that was fine. One comment I would like to make is that we would have loved to have been able to walk on or into some of these training areas rather than just look at empty spaces from 1st floor viewing platform.
Went to a few concerts here over the years, pretty great. A few job fairs too. Nice buildings, bit hard to find exactly where you're going once there but you get the hang of it.
For my under 18’s soccer tour last year when we stayed and we played soccer in the massive stadiums.  The grounds over there are really good.

I’ve been to the AIS two times in the past year and I absolutely love this place. The first time was when I competed at a swim meet. The facilities were wonderful and it was the perfect location for the event. I also enjoyed the AIS merchandise store which stocked a wide variety of branded products. The second time I was in Canberra was for the Australian Running Festival and I decided to come to the AIS for some swimming training. This place is a hidden gem for lap swimming. I have been a swimmer for a significant portion of my life. I’ve been to multiple different pools and battled chaotic pools with zero lane availability. This place is the opposite and it is a dream. I swam on the weekend and weekday nights and there was hardly anyone there. There were two full sized pools open to the public. I really appreciate the way the AIS makes the facility available to the public, I can’t wait to return.  This is the highlight of any trip to Canberra.
When were there in 2016 when we took the freedom Cruise you are not able to go in but enjoy the breeze in the back. We also did a true of the orphanage which part of proceeds went to it.
It was lit! We enjoyed it!
Great locality for an outdoor wedding.
Under renovation but should become one of downtown's best place to visit starting in 2018.
Good

Very educational and entertaining. Great displays with heaps of information in easy to understand formats. Good for kids of all ages. Heaps of parking. Staff friendly and accommodating. Plenty of photo opportunities. Gift shop isn't over priced and has a large range of educational toys. 
Excellent way to pass a few hours.

I took my 22 month old grandson mid march, the tour guide Matt was so interactive and captivating that even as young as he is he went through tour without getting bored, we then spent another couple of hours touching all of the interactive pieces, kids room and out door area. It a definite return place for us

Outside is the best area for kids.  Inside is informative for adults. Pricing on souvenirs well and truly overpriced... other attractions around Canberra selling some items at half the cost. They charge an entry fee so shouldn't need to be so high.  Personally we wouldn't bother going inside again.

Great place to bring kids 3+ years old. Probably better to prep them a bit about large moving dinosaur exhibits. Great hourly tours - interesting for kids and adults. Great staff, very child friendly. Clean toilets and parent room, large gift shop. Outdoor area would benefit from shade sail for kids to play in summer.

Disappointing ESPECIALLY for the cost. Nothing much to see inside but an evolution lesson. The best part is what's free: the dinosaurs outside the front and back that the kids love playing around! Save yourself the trouble and just visit the outside!
It is a great point for sight-seeing and getting refreshed. A lot of cyclists and joggers are seen around.
This was the original lookout. I suspect that the new lookout is better.
There's just something about dams and spillways. Remember to take valuables with you if parking and walking from here.
Fantastic place to chill out and take photos

There are two places you can view Scrivener Dam release water area from either side of the Dam wall.
At the larger carpark on the Governor General side of the Dam wall you have a park like area for shade and a large viewing platform. Across the bridge/ dam wall there is a small parking area to the left  just off the bridge right near the zoo.
To the right there is a large Park land on the peninsula with covered table, chairs & BBQ area. It has a lovely view of the lake looking towards the Governor Generals House and towards the base of Black Mountain. Standing prominent on Black Mountain, is the Telstra Communications Tower overlooking Canberra. The the tower is an ideal navigation guide when traveling around Canberra. 
The views of Canberra from the Tower and Arboretum nearby are beautiful and really give you a sense of the beauty, serenity and life style the City of Canberra has on offer.

We visited for a kids birthday party and it was great. The kids loved the playground. Had their own reptiles show and we got to explore inside to see all the animals. A great place to take kids.
There were even people walking around with reptiles to look at and touch.

World class service; Its so rare to come to a small and intimate animal or in this case reptile exhibit ( park) and receive such great service and patience, as was displayed by Scott who showed us around and was generous with his time to answer any and all of our questions. This is a model which should be copied in big cities around the world.

Great interaction for the kids being able to touch many different reptiles. Excellent experiences and the staff were fantastic with engaging with the kids. Best reptile park / experience we've had. Could have spent many more hours there. Next pack a lunch and enjoy the outdoor play area.
Great little reptile zoo. The volunteers are really helpful and informative too. You can touch a variety of different snakes and lizards. My 3 year old had a great time!
Fantastic place to visit your able to get hands on with some.of the reptiles staff are wonderful. Great place for all ages. Worth the visit and will be back.

A great place to be. The most healthy and happy animals I have seen in a Zoo! We had a fantastic time roaming on our own and also went on 2 tours. Every single staff member is delightful, I do not have anything negative to say it was sensational. We also stayed overnight which is a must do!

Absolutely love it.
I go there quite frequently since my little boy loves being there. The new playground is an absolute highlight for him. He just loves it, and I can hardly get him back home.

The grounds are really nice, and suitable in any weather. The animals all look happy and well looked after. 

It's always been a pleasure to be there, and we will go many more times in the future.

Zoo is very large and clean. Has seating scattered fairly regularly around the paths and plenty of shade. Would recommend going during the week if at all possible as it is much quieter. The annual pass is good value if you would attend the zoo 3+ times in a year. The daily fee really should be lower.

I was very impressed by this place. Great layout, very well kept exhibits and good variety of animals from all around the world. Our kids loved the brand new playground area (Mar '19). Two large cafes on site with all the usual fare. They also have intriguing looking hotel rooms that you can stay in, each one looking over a different animal exhibit... Sip champagne on your balcony and have a visit from a giraffe... Awesome!😀😀

Would happily visit again.

My family have been going to this zoo for years. And each time we have gone there has been amazing improvements to make the zoo nicer to wander and easier to walk around ( you don't need the map if you follow the numbered trails around) I like that they have an aquarium and feeding times, as well as trees surrounding you and shade on hot days. They have a cafe and a gift shop which is great. We will return again😊

It's a great walk up, takes about 40+60 minutes for moderate to slow pace. It's a nice mostly paved path up with a few steps towards the end. Great view of Canberra, the war memorial and parliament house at the top. There's also a water fountain at the top, which is handy. If you don't like walking you can cheat and drive up.

There’s a tap to refill your water bottle at the top of Mount Ainslie. It’s located near the park benches at the lookout. There are no toilets at the lookout. No shelter. There is car parking at the lookout. Excellent views of Canberra and the Australian Capital Territory.

Probably the best panorama of Canberra. You can chest and ride to the summit or stretch your legs with a rewarding walk from behind the Australian War Memorial following the steep but well made and shady zigzag path that tells the story of the Kokoda defence. No toilet or food facilities at summit
One of the best places in Canberra for bushwalking/hiking/trail running. Very well marked out track which is user friendly as well. Recently has been rolled out so that there are less rocky surfaces.
Excellent walk up the mountain, shady, full of wildlife, a must see for all visitors
Beautiful scenery, great wineries!
An enjoyable walk up Mt Majura. Fairly quiet and not too far to the top. Less than 2 hours generally depending on your walking speed.

While it doesn't give you the views that Mt Ainslie has, it does give you two unique ways to reach the top and the views are still pretty good showing you another part of Canberra. 
It's also pretty cool seeing the planes flying into land below you.
The Hackett Gate lets you walk to the top via the ridge of the mountain and the other lets you reach the top by a more direct route.
It's also a bit less crowded than My Ainslie.
Good lookout
Nice walk steep and sporty, awesome view

Glad I went! Interstate visitors and I thought we would be in and out in three minutes...we were there almost an hour! We arrived just in time for the 45minute tour, it was a small group which made it more personal. The tour guides didnt miss a beat and what an experience. There were children in the group who enjoyed themselves and the history of this home. The tour guides even made it more interesting for the kids by doing small things like allowing them to ring the service bells. Really enjoyed the experience and glad i finally went!

Finally ticked this one off my Canberra bucket list. I did the tour with a neighbour and was very pleased with the experience. The guides were knowledgeable and passionate and added a lot of context and insight to what we were able to see - well worth the $7. This is a wonderfully preserved piece of early Canberra and a great insight into life in the 40s/60s.
Beautifully preserved. Feels like you're taking a step back in time

This home was built for the Calthorpe family in 1927, the year the Federal Parliament and public service were transferred to Canberra. Harry and Dell Calthorpe moved to Canberra from Queanbeyan, having seen the potential of the new city first hand through Harry’s role in land auctions in the growing Federal Capital.

The Calthorpes chose the architects Oakley and Parkes to design their home; the same firm that had won a national competition to design suitable houses for the Federal Capital, and had also designed the Prime Minister’s residence, the Lodge.

The house was designed for the hot, dry Canberra summers and to correspond with the Garden City ideal of a free-standing cottage set within a large garden. Like many Canberra houses of this period it has a roughcast exterior finish painted in earthy colours, a tiled roof with shingled gables, arched verandahs and shuttered windows.

Adding to a few treasured items of furniture transferred from their old house, Mrs Calthorpe selected new furniture and household items from Beard Watson & Co. in Sydney. As most of the furnishings and fittings were purchased at the same time, and were carefully cared for by Mrs Calthorpe rather than being replaced, the house and its contents remain excellent examples of the prevailing style of the time.

The Calthorpe Family
Harry Calthorpe was a partner in the stock, station and real estate agency of Woodgers and Calthorpe. The firm conducted the first sale of leases in Canberra in 1924. Harry had served in WW1, sustaining injuries at Gallipoli which saw him return to Australia to work in the recruiting campaign. Harry married Della Ludvigsen in 1917 and their two daughters, Del and Dawn, were born in Queanbeyan.

The girls grew up alongside the new city of Canberra, attending the Church of England Girls’ Grammar School which was a short walk from their home. Del married Captain STG Coleman in 1942, and in 1944 Dawn married Douglas Waterhouse, an entomologist at the CSIRO where Dawn worked as a laboratory assistant.

Harry Calthorpe died in 1950, and his wife Dell remained living in the house until shortly before her death in 1979. In the mid 1980s, as many in our community were becoming concerned about the loss of Canberra’s heritage, the Federal Government purchased Calthorpes’ House. It is now preserved as a window into a family’s life in our city’s early years.

A guide to the rooms
Calthorpes’ House is divided into areas based on function, with the public rooms grouped at the front of the house, the family’s private rooms are separated by the hall and passage and the domestic work areas are toward the rear of the house.

Interior decoration
The stained blackwood panelling in the hall is mirrored in the ceiling beams of the dining room and the ceiling of the sitting room. Other timber used in the house has been stained to match, while the walls are rough-rendered and painted.   The public rooms are encircled by a plate rail for the display of ornaments.

The rooms were very comfortable and fashionable and have altered little since the Calthorpes’ time. The gramophone, pianola, records and bridge cards reflect the family’s entertainment and pastimes. Mrs Calthorpe was a keen bridge player, and many of the items on display were won in bridge competitions.

Kitchen, pantry and bathroom
There was a new focus on the science of hygiene in the 1920s which is reflected in the use of easily cleaned surfaces such as tiles and linoleum. The Calthorpes welcomed the new domestic technology of a toaster, iron and fan, but they still relied on an ice chest which required daily supplies of block ice. The stove burned solid fuel, but was later replaced by an electric Early Kooka stove.

In the 1920s tradesmen delivered most household supplies to the back door. A tradesman’s safe is located on the back porch in which goods would be placed if the house’s occupants were not at home. On the wall in the pantry is a grocer’s reminder list made of tin.

.
A great window into Canberra in the 1920-50s
Always open, great for quite self reflection and prayer.
Nice to find the chapel open to visitors. Lots of history.
Superb
Amazing

One of the few truly old-fashioned traditional sandstone parish churches in Canberra. But not original, it was the Rookwood Cemetery Station from Sydney and imported stone by stone to Ainslie. The mods were sympathetic and so is a delight to visit even if you are not religiously inclined.
They are always very very Helpful there and just a great bunch of people
Very beautiful place, definitely worth it to be seen in Canberra!
Fantastic stain glassed window behind the altar of the church.
One of the oldest church in Canberra.

An improved scene. The show has gotten way better this year and I'm sure it will continue to get better. Heaps of stalls ranging from bubbles to crocodile teeth bracelets. There are some aspects that could be improved like, the map not having the stalls (Or at least food stalls), not having a list of the stalls, and it all felt a little unorganised, if you were able to group the stalls together into categories it would be a much better event.

They rarely change it up and don't do much to reduce the bad smell of the barn animals. There's too many near the "attractions." And too many places get away with charging $7 for orange juice... At least the price to get in has dropped
A lot better than some of the other shows I've been to. Heaps to see and do. Fairly reasonable prices.

Took bloody 1.5hr to get to parking and top of that $5 for parking fees, if they charge they should provide better service. 
Good for little kids and teenagers. Stores are lil expensive too. Wouldnt recommend for adults unless u taking kids with u.
Love going to the show. Way cheaper to get in this year which was nice.
Museum and viewing area provides a nice self guided tour. Access to the operational dishes is not permitted. A great place to visit.
Drive from Canberra was very nice and scenic.Museum is small but lots of information to seek. Nice place for space lovers.

Construction of the complex began in June 1963 with operations commencing in December 1964, in time to support the Mariner 4 spacecraft encounter with Mars. The centrepiece of the complex was the 26-metre antenna (Deep Space Station 42). Two years later a crewed spaceflight wing was added to the complex to assist with the Apollo missions to the Moon. By 1970 the complex featured a power station, and facilities to manage the sewage and water supplies, while a cafeteria, and sleeping accommodation fed and housed the many workers on site. During early 1969 construction started on a new antenna. At 73 metres in height and weighing more than seven million kilograms, the then 64-metre antenna (Deep Space Station 43) took nearly four years to complete. The need for such an antenna was brought about by the increasing amounts of data received and the rapidly expanding distances that spacecraft were travelling. The new 64-metre antenna was more than six times as sensitive as the existing 26-metre antenna, and therefore could extend the useful lifetime of a spacecraft as its signal became weaker the further it was from Earth.

During the 1980s the Voyager spacecraft travelled billions of kilometres to investigate the ‘gas giants’ Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus and Neptune. Over such distances, the signals from the spacecraft would be extremely weak and requiring more sophisticated equipment on Earth to receive them.

Consequently, in 1980 the 26-metre antenna was upgraded to become a 34-metre antenna, improving the surface of the dish and adding higher frequency receiving capabilities. Similarly in 1987, the 64-metre antenna was upgraded to 70 metres in diameter. Even today, the 70-metre antenna is the largest steerable parabolic antenna in the Southern Hemisphere.

When Honeysuckle Creek Tracking Station closed in December 1981, the 26-metre antenna was relocated to Tidbinbilla and renamed Deep Space Station 46 where it was used for spacecraft positioned close to the Earth. It was retired in 2009.

In 1986 the construction of a new high efficiency 34-metre antenna (Deep Space Station 45) was completed to provide better reception at higher frequencies. The antenna was completed in time for the Voyager 2 encounter with Uranus, where it was used in conjunction with the 70-metre antenna to provide even greater sensitivity for the reception of signals. Deep Space Station 45 was decommissioned in 2016.
For anyone with any interest in space this is a 'must visit' place and worth the short drive out from Canberra. Very informative displays and the 4k screening of short space films were brilliant!

If you are interested in space, then this place is worth a visit
It's free
Only negative, no nasa products to buy

Went to see free exhibition (Cook and the Pacific) with the kids, one in a pram. Staff were great, no issues. Will need to go back sans children, so I can have a proper look.

Not the first exhibition I have seen there, always well curated and full of interesting items.

Great location overlooking the lake, surrounded by public art and part of the parliamentary triangle. Has a cafe, bookshop, paid parking. 

They have a reading room too.
A good place for kids, safe and continent facilities for them.

Wonderful place to do some studying or research.
Chair looks comfy and the view from the windows is just relaxing.
River side walking trail let you relax your brain if you study in the library for extended hours.

Fantastic resource for all, not just those who live in Canberra. Special mention to Sonja who was incredibly helpful when my friend and I visited. Good to know that the hold every book published in Australia!

A national treasure with a collection rivaling the great libraries of the world. Calm environment for research and study; excellent amenities (clean toilets,  free lockers, water fountains). There is also a bit for the visitor too with exhibits and galleries on rotation.  Bookplate is a very popular restaurant with spectacular views across the lake,  and they cater for vegans. Free wifi and ample parking.

This is a very well laid out gallery. There are many early works, including many of prominent Aboriginal people and early pioneers. There are sculptures as well as paintings and sketches. Although I found much of it interesting, there are probably too many displays to make seeing the whole gallery a totally enjoyable experience. On the other hand, there is so much information about each of the items that it would be difficult to rush through too quickly.  It's great that our explorers, Australia's original people and business, sport and political figures are acknowledged with a portrait in the gallery. There is paid car parking below and a cafe.

Amazing! Spent hours here. So interesting and so much to see. We didn’t want to leave. On the day we visited it was quiet and relaxed and the perfect activity for a cold rainy day in Canberra. Will be back here again for sure.
A beautiful space. The collection is very diverse and incredibly high quality. The staff are friendly and helpful.

Mostly really good. 
Did have issues getting around with the pram and nappy bag as security was pretty tough. Recommend you take minimal on the day. Very basic parent room but it does the job. 
Echoed a bit (noticed when my newborn wouldn't stop farting lol). 
Well displayed artwork and pretty easy parking. Cafe was pretty good too.

NGA is a world class gallery, a large gallery comparable to those interstate and overseas. There are permanent and touring exhibitions, featuring a mix of contemporary and traditional art from Western and global artists. Something for everyone, suited to all ages and physical abilities. Good selection of indigenous art, and well curated selection of Australian art generally.

Highly recommend the Yum Cha from Dumpling Inn. The staff are always really friendly, the food is fresh and very tasty. The cheapest dish is $5.50 all the way up to $8.80. 

Good selection of non alcoholic and alcoholic beverages. Beautiful interior and in a quiet part of the shopping complex so plenty of parking right out the front.

I have been twice, both times with my Chinese friend who is very fussy and she loves the place.  The food is outstanding.  As with yum char you have to be quick to get the really good stuff and what I love about this place is that unlike other yum char places that I have been to is that the majority of the food is good and you want to eat it .The radish cake is really, really good, deep fried chicken wings are outstanding, chicken feet are the best that I have had.  I don't like Chinese sweets but this is one of the few places that I eat and enjoy these.
Yum cha here is decent. I enjoy the food here and staff always friendly.
Lovely people but no vegan options
Fantastic food and service full marks
Became our 'go-to' for coffee this week. Their young Barista does a very good coffee. Pastries are great.
很好的选择。

We came for the food and it did not disappoint. Good value for money and authentic. The outdoor seating area was very dirty with food stains on the tables, chairs and the paving around the shop. Even the front door was covered in hand marks. If you want to eat at the shop something to keep in mind. I trust the kitchen is spotless...

Best place in Canberra for your kebab, snack and pide needs. Never disappointed in terms of quality or quantity. Friendly service and always helpful. I mostly go there for their kebab plates which comes with rice, and meat and salad of your choice. Also got banquet meals for groups which are well worth the money. If you have a group of 10, get the pack for 8, you may still have food leftover. Will definitely visit again and again.

This is the best Turkish takeaway in the ACT, and possibly further than that. The staff in the shop are always fast with in putting together your order and the food has never been anything short of delicious.
The kebabs are the highlight. Situated in a good spot in Yarralumla shops, and just up the road from the lake and watersport facilities.

By far the best kebab and halal snack packs I've had in Canberra or anywhere, they make their own kebab bread which is really nice. Their HSPs are generous sizes and the meat is always good. only thing I find is that the chips are sometimes undercooked.

There is no doubt in my mind that this is the single best kebab shop ever opened. Truly perfect in every way: Generosity, price, friendliness, taste. I can't get over how soft and fluffy the wraps for the kebabs are. This kebab shop is how I convince people from around Australia to visit Canberra. And every single one of them has so far agreed this is the best kebab ever. Absolute. Unanimous. Fact.

Even the front door was covered in hand marks. If you want to eat at the shop something to keep in mind. I trust the kitchen is spotless...

And every single one of them has so far agreed this is the best kebab ever. Absolute. Unanimous. Fact.

Quite literally the best service I've ever had, on multiple occasions. The waiting staff are are brilliant and accommodating, even in the busiest of circumstances. Food is always delicious so compliments to all the cooks, they always look like they're having fun. I don't ever hesitate to recommend Belluci's
Great service and awesome lunch deals. Belluci's always has great food :)
Incredible food, very professional service. A little over priced.
Expensive and not value for money. The meals are small and not great when you compare them to what they cost. Staff are great and friendly but sadly the food doesn’t rate.

It is convenient, the Italian menu never disappoints and the staff are always welcoming. On the downside, some of the dishes are on the pricey side but always quality and once it gets busy And it always does, it is really noisy. But I shouldn't complain my downsides are just a result of its popularity, not criticisms!
Note though the chocolates, and pastries are good, my rating is for his bread which is fantastically flavourful.
Had a delicious warm brownie with a hot chocolate. Would definitely go again. Love the locally produced  honey I bought there too.
out of savoury food when we went for lunch...bought some great chutney which went well on a crusty bread roll

Returned to visit Bruno's after 30 years - Bruno remembered me and was welcoming (I worked in a wine shop next door to the original shop).  The chocolates are still fantastic and the coffee and cakes are great.
Delicious bread. Amazing chocolate 🙂

AVOID IF YOU CAN.
I’ve never been able to buy everything on my shopping list as their shelves are almost never stocked. Staff are somewhat helpful and I often see them throw produce into place which explains why they’re all bruised. 
Better to drive the extra mile and visit a store that’s fully stocked with happy looking produce.

Woolworths average standard. BWS Liquor store Whole precinct pretty good. Pay for parking, max 2 hr. Wide selection coffee shops, snacks, breakfasts. Down side, several beggars sitting around. Wouldn't go there if woolies wasn't there.
Better than so many other Woolworths in Canberra
Like all Woolworths they are competitive have gòod variety fresh fruit and veggies ECT  and in big complex also plenty parking
Slightly infected though seems to provide enough good service and products
Great service & a great location. Although named as (a wine bar,) it certainly has more of a restaurant vibe. Delicious fresh flavours with a slight tang & spice, it's good value for money in Civic

I went for two for one Monday and can't believe I have never been to this restaurant before. While the wine part of the meal wasn't the best, I could not speak more highly of the food. I was very very impressed. And I would say it is some of the best Thai food I have had in some time.
Great value of you're the first two for one on Monday and Tuesday!
Food was pretty good and we'll priced
Under staffed although service was decent when they eventually got to you. Food wasn't great and very expensive for what it was - they used way too much fish sauce in the dish as well.

Great location and ambiance for friends to hang out and catch up. Really great coffee and plenty of things to try from. I love the great chocolate selections they have. The staff are polite and courteous. I like to try things out and most of the time, I love it. I am glad I was able to go there almost every week. It is a little bit fancy place, but totally worth everything.

Always a Lovley visit. The staff are nice and are always very happy to help if needed. The chocolate, what can I say? Is to die for! The coffee is good and the platters of tasters are a must have! Good for all ages as they have something for everyone. I would definitely recommend for someone who has a sweet tooth (or not) thank you!

Loved the coffee, loved the vibe! A brilliant place to hang out. Also, the hot chocolate is awesome and the selection of desserts here is pretty cool. The only thing that stops me from going here every week is the price - a little too fancy but it’s worth it!

Love this place! Am a regular. The chocolates are amazing and so are the dessert offerings. Recently tried the crumpets and the quality of the butter and jam made a simple tea something to remember. 
Some staff are more courteous than others making customer service slightly inconsistent between visits, but overall excellent!
Solid dessert chain. Pretty much what you'd expect. Decent chocolate and a reasonable price. Nothing too stand out about it.

Maestral Seafood Restaurant in Weston is a family-owned and run restaurant that serves Croatian and Mediterranean cuisine. The food is always consistent and delicious and the service is always great. There are so many options on the menu and the special board always has yummy dishes! This restaurant is a family favourite of ours and I have been several times in the last 9 years. The first time I visited it was delicious and every time I've been since it's been consistently good. If you love seafood in a relaxed and casual atmosphere you will love Maestral. The venue is small so booking is recommended!
Beautiful food. Very delicious. Love how quaint the restaurant was. Great service and friendly staff. I'm new to this area and I will definitely eat there again.
The service and the quality of the food was awesome. I am still in awe of the depth of flavour in our meal. Good little bottle shop around the corner for BYO.

We recently enjoyed a wonderful alfresco summer dinner at Maestral. We had last been there a few years ago and we were just as impressed this time. The food is excellent and the staff very friendly. It remains one of Canberra's best dining experiences.
Fantastic restaurant, food and service is 5 star. Only bad thing is it's so good it's hard to get a reservation because everyone else has booked in.

Tasteless, overpriced and average service.
Ordered the selection of breads to share for entrée which was average. 
Had a seafood risotto for main which was tasteless and unseasoned. Had to request salt and pepper to be brought to the table to give some taste to my meal. Seafood was overcooked in the risotto. The prawns and Calamari was rubbery and the fish (2 very small pieces) was dry. Minimal seafood for a seafood risotto. 
Did finish with dessert which was large servings and reasonable cost. 
Would only return for a dessert after eating a more pleasant meal elsewhere.

Best King Prawns and the Calamari!!

I went in there with my family for dinner on the weekend. we shared prawns and calamari for the entrée and they were out class, main course was as good, we ordered two pasta and two main meals. Good serving size and will recommend the braised Lamb shoulder to all the lamb lovers out there.. Thanks Tosolinis for the fun night!

I went Tosolini's this morning as was rewarded the "best breakfast" in Canberra... must say I was extremely disappointed!!  First of all they do not have any single piece of fruit on the menu, how comes the best breakfast does not include any kind of fruits? Second, the green tea was a very small pot and not good at all. I ordered brown toast with jam and they charged me the jam separately, unbelievable!! first place where they charged me the jam separately... and the toast was not cheap at all, crazy ehh?? Finally, when I went to pay, they do not accept credit card transactions under 20 AUD and they do not split bills.... and I must say the attention was not good at all!! Conclusion, I still can not understand how this place is considered the best breakfast place in Canberra in 2013... I've been here since last two weeks and even the smallest and shinny coffee shop is better than Tosolini's
Went with a group from work, service was slow, food was ordinary and way over priced for what we got.  Wouldn't recommend this place to anyone.

Very crap! Service was poor missed out on one of our meals. Nearly had to throw a glass at someone to get a second drink, but just gave up in the end, paid and went home. Really poor service and food. Would not recommend.

Had explosive diarrhea and acid stomach 10 hours after having my birthday dinner here. My husband and I shared every course except for the ice-cream dessert that I ate all by myself. He had cheese instead. He did not get sick. I cannot be 100% certain what made me sick. After all, who can!

We spent about $400 for food (4 courses each) and wine (3 glasses each). The third courses (beef for me, fish for him) both tasted very good - which deserved 4 stars. But the rest of the meal had from average quality to odd combinations of tastes, which deserved 3 stars at most.

Value for money would feel average if I had not got sick soon afterwards. 

All things considered, I give the entire experience 2 to 3 stars.

(Perhaps losing a bit of weight isn’t entirely a bad thing .... hope I feel better soon ....)

Excellent meal at Aubergine. Every dish was a delight and the matched wines were a perfect accompaniment.

The service was well paced and I never felt like they were rushing me for the next sitting. The sommelier was knowledgeable and friendly, taking to time to explain the wine choices.

The only small complaint was the room was a little hot, maybe the A/C wasn’t coping with the heat wave weather that well.

I’ll keep searching, however I’m not sure food and wine get better than this? A most deserving regular recipient of Canberra’s best restaurant. My wife and I went for our anniversary and chose the degustation + premium wine package and it was flawless. Go ahead, make a booking and try this for yourself
Simply brilliant! The staff are really friendly and the food is to die for. Also, the matching wines selection is a MUST!
Best in Canberra. Would have given 5 star only if server haven't serve me the wrong kind of bread. Lucky I am only sensitive to Gluten and am not celiac.

Fine dining in Canberra 🔝! We had a work dinner there so there was few of us we got the $70 banquet that had a little of everything! The service was a bit slow but the place was packed! Great selection of wines 😍
Not recommended. I had to wait for an 30 minutes to get served. Waitress and staff were all rude. I suggest you look better alternatives for dining.

The food was absolutely delicious and well balanced  . The service attentative and friendly , it s a little too dark in there so one cannot see the beautifully presented dishes well enough. But definitely a place to enjoy

Had my lunch today there with my wife, and everything seemed awkward!!

We arrived at 13:30 (restaurant closes 14:30) and we were greeted by the waiter
- How can I help you? 
- (Seriously!! First time to hear such a greeting at a restaurant) A table for two please.
- Let me check with the kitchen if still open
- (Seriously again!! Like, WTH, are you doing here if the kitchen is closed, they would've informed you early on, and it's still 13:30)

So we waited for his confirmation then got seated. He literally threw the napkins at our laps. 

Food was fine, anything but authentic. Small portion,  e.g., a small portion of rice to share

Paid more than what the experience was worth.
Ottoman is a 1970s restaurant struggling to adapt to a modern world. Outmoded food, slow service, and decrepit decor. Would not go back, there are much nicer places in Canberra!
